title: For Sale:  Underwood US M-1 Carbine WWII
postcontent:
This is a nearly all Underwood WWII M-1 Carbine. The only piece thai I see not Underwood is the front sight. It IS USGI, but a post war replacement. Excellent finish on all parts. Strong Cartouche on the stock. Underwood recieved the coveted " E for Excellence " award from the US Government for their rifles all through their production period. N $1100 OBO. 
There are two kinds of 30 Cal. carbines … . One that loses its value over time ( a commercially made rifle ), and one that is an investment….that is, it will at least HOLD its value, and likely INCREASE in value over time. ( a genuine U.S Carbine .Caliber 30 M1 rifle , made during WWII). You DO get what you pay for
As well as being an important part of the United States Military history, you can defend your home and family with it. It is also easy for anyone in the family to shoot…. Very controllable, with plenty of punch .  Just as important, you can find parts for it if something needs to be replaced ( not always true with a commercially made rifle ).   

The rifles that I have listed from my collection, are all investment quality USGI rifles .  You decide what will be best for you in the long run…

FCG is surplus as modified by Century Arms - no upgrade or modification has been made to the Century trigger/disconnector/searUS made CS Gas Piston is from CAI  (922R part)Action parts :  Carrier, Striker, Bolt, Firing Pin, Top cover, and Springs are all stock Czech Military Suplus EXCEPT:-Bolt has been tuned for proper CAI receiver alignment and operation.-Carrier has been modified by tig welding the required push-down-plate ("tab") on to it -- to extend disconnector dwell time during cycling (often refered to as "being Tabbed") -- this "tab" results in disconnector timing that emulates the original Full-Auto disconnector interaction on the sear, preventing a common vz58 issue Called the "Hermex or Gremlin" effect where the striker (linear hammer) rides forward with the bolt before the trigger is pressed.-Ejector was tuned to accomidate ejection pattern to 98% right exit, thus enabling the potential use of MAGwedge full top rail option. -A Polenar Tactical rapid bolt release prototype was installed to operate with the stock mag release.  I was a beta tester of these bolt releases for them. title: For Sale:  **USED** Japanese Arisaka Rifle - Koishikawa Arsenal 63401 - Type99
postcontent: Japanese Arisaka Rifle - World War II - 38 CarbineCondition:Good. Asking: $200.00. Cash only. No trades. Note: bolt is damaged - bolt and all it’s parts are included. More pics available upon request.http://oldmilitarymarkings.com/japanese_markings.htmlThe Japanese manufactured over 6.4 million rifles and carbines in the 40 years from 1906 to 1945. Most of these rifles were still in use during the Sino-Japanese War of the 1930s and the Pacific War of the 1940s. During the war and subsequent American occupation of Japan, thousands of these rifles found their way to the United States as war souvenirs, making them one of the most common foreign military firearms available in the country.The Arisaka rifles are named for Colonel Nariaki Nariakira Arisaka, who headed a commission during the 1890s which was charged with developing a new rifle to replace the earlier models such as the Murata. The Arisaka rifles were designated with the year of the current emperor's reign. Thus, the Type 38 rifle was designed in the 38th year of the reign of Emperor Meiji (1905), and the Type 44 carbine was adopted in the 44th year of his reign (1911). During the reign of Hirohito, rifles were designated by the last one or two digits of the adoption year according to the standard Japanese calendar. Thus, the Type 99 rifle was adopted in Japanese calendar year 2599 (1939), and the Type 2 paratroop rifle was adopted in calendar year 2602 (1942).A chrysanthemum with 16 petals (the symbol of the Japanese Emperor) was usually stamped on the receiver of rifles manufactured for the Imperial Japanese Army, indicating that the rifle belonged to the Emperor.
